This paper deals with social choice functions and their manipulation, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The use of Kelly's preference extension and the study of strategyproofness suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves mathematical analysis and proofs, which could place it in the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the study of social choice functions and their properties could also be relevant to multi-agent systems (cs.MA).
